{"/service/ndnp/mimtptc/batch_mimtptc_inkster_ver01/data/sn88063294/00340589129/1946012101/1071.xml":{"full_text":"2-C\n57 Steel Plants Shut\n15.500 Join\nStrike Her<\u2018\nFifty-srven plants t mployinp 15. .500 workers in \u2019he\nDetroit area, were dosed today by the nationwide steel\nstrike.\nMore than 118.000 Michigan workers were made idle\n\u2022y industrial disputes, most of them in the Detroit area.\nApproximately 100,000 General Motors Corp. employes\nhave been on strike lor 02 days.\nAnother 3.000 workers at the Dodpe main plant were\nlaid off last week because of a shortage caused by the glass\nindustry strike, which was settled last night.\nA iarge number of other plants in industries dependent\non steel will bo forced to close in Detroit and Michigan soon\nif the strike persists.\nNTRIkt KS .11 Ml* 1 N\nSeventy-two plants <mpl<>\\ ng\n23.000 worker*. were involved\nthroughout Michigan.\nWorkers at the ('.real Lakes\nSteel Corn* plant in Ernrso. when\n7.118 are employed, lumped th<\ngun\u201d Friday night. 18 hours be\nfore the zero hour, closing the\nfchopv\nSmall picket lino were estab\nlished in the snow and slush at\nall struck plants between mid\nnight and 6 a. m. today Thomas\nShane. Detroit district director of\nthe United Steel Workers' Union,\nCIO. said.\nBTOC k I KON IMONS\nGreat Lakes Steel has storked\na freighter at H*nna Furnace Co\nwith enough prevuuons for a long\nstrike, union leaders said Sixty\nforemen and salaried office work\ners are being houned for emer\ngency use in the maintenance of\nihe three blast furnaces, coke and\nby-prodin t ovens, it wa* claimed.\nOther supervisory and salaried\nworkers remaim'd in the main\nGreat Lakes plant in Ecorse over\nthe week-end. it was reported\nUnion pickets who stayed on the\nyob throughout the night said the\ncompany had taken into the plant\nlarge stock* of provisions.\nSalaried workers were bring al\nlowed to enter the gates and no\ndisturbances were reported.\nTemporary housing ua\u00bb con\nstructed for those workers re\nmaining inside.\nGIVE TO STRIKE I l \\l>\nSome union members complained\nthat they were asked to give 40\nper cent of their pay to the union\nfor a strike fund and a number\nreportedly went home at Hanna\nFurnace.\nA spokesman for I>ocal 129 V\ndenied that there was any com\npulsion in contributions, but *atd\nmany, including union officials,\nwere contributing all their pay.\nPICKETED AT MIDNIGHT\nThe ftvo Detroit area plant*\nwhere picketing was started at\nmidnight are:\nAluminum Co of America. 3311\nDunn, where 525 are employed,\nRotary Electric Steel Co.. 21400\nMound. 700: McLouth Steel Corp..\n300 S. Livemoia. fiOO all in De\ntroit, and the Repuhljc St\u00bb*el\nCorp., Frrndale. 152. and Michi\ngan Seamless Tube Co, S\nLyons. 225.\nShane said all picketing would\nhe done by \"token\" lines because\nno trouble was anticipated Po\nlice. however, were on duty to see\nthat order wa* preserved.\nENTER ON FAMES\nAt every plant. Shane added,\narrangements have been made to\nBusiness, Industry, Government,\nAre Calling You\nPrepare now' for business or government service\nin M ichigan's largest business school.\nThe Business Institute, Michigan Building\n220 Bagiev Ave., Detroit\n_T Day and Eicninft St bool I\nI MR. ARTHT'R F. TULL, President,\nmprO\\<\u2018 Avp. T\u2014(rolt. 2fi\nvour Please mall me free ropy of booklet\n\"Career* in RusinesH,\u2019*\nearning\n|\u00bbo%V4>r NAME\nMail Coupon NOVI' \\I\u00bbI>KESS\nfp NOKWWIST tAtSAGf to\nwi c I NEW YORK\njpg' I MILWAUKEE W\n\"*S 1 MINNEAPOLIS- i\n1 ST. PAUL\nSEATTLE V\nI ond 20 other e.t.e* j\nNEW LOW FARES.\nj NOk .HWEST AIRLINES\nTHI DETROIT TIMES\nIn rmit maintenance and salaried\nwinkers, carrying passes, to enter\nThe other Detroit area steel\nplants and the number of work\nis affected by the strike are:\nR C Mahnn Co, 4*7, Intrttuitonat Con\nunit UmMi.t .in I'o ralinrr Hi r\n>r r lr* loii'ejmr Co hS, Jrnli\n11 W.fih 19 5 C. .1 CUUfOO. 1*\nO. s\u25a0, i r.ip 255 Crntral Stwl