. Nnv York, said in an article\nin Hygna that cancer was being\ncured every day, but that many\nsufferers waited too long before\nseeking medical attention.\nTHE WEATHER\nDetroit and vicinity eirtly cloudy \u00bbnrt\nmuch toldei tonlcht. lowest trniprraturr about\nfl Tucsdsy partly cloudy and continued cold\nShipper** forecast Protect \u00bbhtpmer)!\u00bb eltir\nln\u00bb the nest 3fl hour* for North, -10 dc\n*rees. west. aero. east. 10 south, A.\nDETROIT DAT*\nTemfierature* Sunday: HUhest 27 decree*\nlowest 1 2 mean 2(1\nDeparture from normal tempersture Sunday\n\u20144 decree*\nDeparture from normal tempersture since\n\u2022Isn 1 *ll* decree*\nTemnertture* \"ns year Ago lode*- Hl\u00bbh*wt.\n44 decree* l\"we\u00abt, ST mean 1*\nTemperature* since lA7J- H|\u00bbtie\u00bbt A J de\nCtee* In lt\u00bb0\u00ab> lowest 4 tn 1424\nRelative humidity Sunday 1 TO a m\n7\\<v. 7 TO a m 7A\" 1 tn p 0- 40V.\n730 p m \u00bb4't.\nCreel pit at inn In last 24 hours endlnc \u00bbt\nS 30 a m tnd*y IS tnch\nDeparture from normal precipitation *lnce\nJan i SS Inch.\nDec ree day* for Aunda* Jan 20 4s\nNormal for Jan 20 41\nAccumulated dec.'ee day* thl* month 442\nNormal dryer da<* fat I* >u\u00bb v IAS\nMon.. J\u00abn. 21, 1946\nTruman Urges\nNational Unity\n(Continued from Page One)\np\\|t\u00bbrtP(l that ttii* \u00bbu\u00abTti\u00bb will\ncoot lone in a %a\u00bbt majority of\n(he easrs arising In the months\nahead.\n\u201cHowever, every one who\nrealize* the extreme need for\na swift and orderly reconver\nsion must feel a deep concern\nabout the number of major\nstrike* now in progress. If long\ncontinued, these strikes could\nput a heavy brake on our pro\ngram.\u201d\n'lTie President called anew for\naction on his entire domestic pro\ngram, including his proposal that\nstrike* he held in abeyance while\nfact-finding hoards investigate\nlabor-management disputes.\nI on l r LL EMPLOI MINT\nFull employment and greater\nproduction remained the keynote\nof his recommendations. But he\nstruck one new note in calling\nfor \"maior steps\u201d hy the govern\nment to enforce anti-trust laws\nsuspended in a number of fields\nduring the war- to \u201crnrouragr\nnew and competing enterprises\nin every way.\u201d\nIn the military field, Mr. Tru\nman recommended an army-navy\nstrength of 2,000.000 men for this\ncalendar year and said continu\nance of the draft beyond its ex\npiring date ot May 16 will be\nnecessary if enlistments do not\nobtain necessary replacements of\nthose demobilized.\nAugmenting his earlier foreign\npolicy statement s. he asserted\nAmerican peace policy must rest\n\"upon justice no less than uj>on\npower.\u201d\nPLANS ATOM SAFEGUARDS\nHe urged the \"greatest dis\npatch\u201d in the world of the United\nNations commission to control\nHiorine energy and expressed\n\"great hope\u201d for development of\n\u201cmutually effective safeguards\u201d in\nsuch control. He *aid he also be\nlieved il possible that the atomic\nhomh will he outlawed as a war\nw eafion.\nWhile reser\\ ing for a late!\nmessage detailed discussion of the\nproposed $3,750,000,000 loan to\nBritain. Mr. Truman said gtant\ning this credit would contribute\nto \"easing the transition problem\nof one of our major partners in\nthe war.\u201d\nThe Chief Executive said he\nhad combined the first postwar\nbudget with his state of the union\nmessage because \u201cit has become\nnecessary to formulate and de\ntermine the government fxrogram\nin the light of national economic\nconditions as a whole.\u201d\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK\n\"Such an approach,\" he as\nserted. \"ha** Itfi'onie imperative\nif the American political anil\nfcnntimir lystem la to aucceevl\nunder the condition* of eco\nnomic instability and uncer\ntainty which we have to face.\u201d\nIn an int toduction entitled\n\"from war to peace\u2014the year\nof decision.\u201d he declared the be\nginning of lf>46 finds this rouniry\n\"strong and deservedly confident.\"\nlit* said that for the immediate\nfuture the business prospects \u201care\ngenerally so favorable that there\nis danger of such feverish and op\nportunistic activity that our grave\npostwar problems may be neg\nlected\nWASHING\nMACHINE\nParts and Service\nWHITE\nWRINGER ROLLS\n|J 1 Dstrsit'l Oily f setsry\nAwgL HI A ,b\u00df, l*4d Sondes for\nAPEX 1900\nfi ln! Hi BOTORLX\nPaVyW faultless\nI WHIRLPOOL\nr CATARACT\nop*n Monday Eves. Till\nOf a'Ctock\nWestern Appliance Service\n(Formerly tho 1400 Shoal\nSOSO GRAND RIVER\nI Block Bolow Olympic\nTY 4-1900 TY 4-1901\nFRAZERI\nPAINT j\nBU 1 -a HAJkK** VARNISHES\nfOOR Til lUt ENAMELS\nPAIt 0 \\A PAINTING\nyY SUPPLIES\n9 FRAZER PAINT CO. STORES J\n747 j HUBBAEO\n3707 MICHIGAN AVI\nOn* Hoci W\u00bb\u00bbl pi Junction\n10100 1 WARREN of Codilioc\n3*ol FINKCI of Holmwr\n3000 McNICMOLS\n17000 GRANO RIVER\nof K#\u00abfucfcy\nShortage\nIn l*lass\nAlthough the 13* week glass\nstrike i> ended, normal production\nwill not be possible for six months,\nA, J, Roche, Detroit manager of\nthe Pittsburgh Plate Glass Co.,\nI said today.\nThe wage strike of 15,000 glass\nworkers ended with the signing\n\u00ab*f a contract in Toledo, national\nheadquarters of the union\nL. G. Bryan, vice president of\nLihbey-Owens-Ford, signed for\n\u2022the manufacturers and interna\ntional officers of the Federation\nof Glass, Ceramic and Silica Sand\nWorkers, CIO, represented the\nunion.\nRoche said supplies wanild start\ntrickling into the IVtroit area\nwithin the next few days.\nShortage of glass has caused\nmany delays in automobile pro\nduction. Roche pointed out. Pitts\nburgh Glass supplies Chrysler,\nHudson. Packard and Nash and\nprovides a limited supply to 4*Y>rd.\nLil)he>-Owens-Fdi d s u p pi i C s\nGenera! Motors.\nState Vet Care\nSeen as Model\nI\nMichigan\u2019s plan for home town\nmedical care for veterans may\nserve as a model lot the rest of\nthe nation, according to Col J. I).\nHarding of the Veterans\u2019 Admin\nistration.\nCol. Harding addressed the\nMichigan State Medical Society\nannual county secretaries' confer\nence in the Wardell-Sheraton yes\nterday.\nThe Michigan society was the\nfirst group to sign a contract for\nI home tow n care of veterans with\nthe Veterans\u2019 Administration\nI Co!. Harding, who came from\nWashington, outlined a routine to\nhe followed in the care of men\nwith service-connec'ed disabilities.\nBirth of Hitler s Son\nTo Eva in '3B Reported\nNEW YORK, Jan. 21.- The\nBrazzaville radio said today that\na son was horn to Adolf Hitler\nand Eva Braun at San Remo.\nItaly. Dec. 31, 1938.\nThe radio added that a year\nlater, in the early morning of\nJan. 1, a German foreign office\nmember was arrested by the Ges\ntapo in Munich for \"having stated\nduring the festivities: \u2018today, the\nj Fuehrer s son celebrates hie\nI birthday\u2019.\u2019*\nTwo Jewelers Robbed\nGRAND RAPIDS. Jan. 21 lAP)\n\u2014Three men and a woman who\nsmashed windows in two west side\njewelry stores and looted them of\n$2,000 worth of merchandise es\ncaped after firing four shots at a\npursuing police car.\n0\nVI p l*ut the String in\nSKIRTS\nCLEANED I\nPRESSED JHr\nUr to S ploats\nyuMrai\nthe aft\n\u00bbTMI Till\n13973 GRATIOT\nTwo Block* E ol McNickoli\n10734 W JEFFERSON\nRiwor louq*\n14701 KERCMEVAI\nNoor Ckolmsn\nONI NEAR YOU\nCrimes Thwart\nPolice Cleanup\n(Continued from Page One)\nafter forcing her and a clerk j\nMorris Nosanchuck, 40, of 16906\nMonica into the rear ot the store.\nTwo Negroes took sl3 from!\nGeorge Sengstock, 43. of 1841 j\nSuperior on Orleans near Gar\nfield. A Negro gunman netted $2\nin the holdup of Alfred Sharp, 26.\nof 540 Alger.\nMargaret Speight. 16, of 9930\nCarlin, was robbed of $25 in\nfront of 13104 W. Chicago. Mrs.\nMaggie Turner, 678 Harper, lost\nher purse containing $1 60 when\ntwo men strong-armed her at\nHarper and Rivard.\nAaron Kutnik. of 2993\nClements was assaulted by two\nthugs near his store at 3811 W.\nWarren. The men fieri when Kut\nnik screamed for help.\nNettie Robinson. 31. of 19775\nRose I awn said two youths, one\nabout 8 years old. failed in an\neffort to get her purse after\nknocking her down near her\nhome.\nPURSE SNATCHED\nMildred Swaczyk. 26. of 2645 E.\nFerry, reported a !4egro snatched\nher purse containing $lO and a\ndiamond ring early today on East\nFerry, near St. Aubin.\nCharles Cuthbert, 21. of 3468\nCass told police two men who\nentered his cab at Fast Jefferson\nand Dubois produced a pistol and\nrobbed him of s2l.\nVirginia Fraser. 28. of 16833\nStoepel reported that a gang of\nfive youths took her purse con\ntaining $6 as she walked on Dela\nware. near Poe. last night.\nPatrolman Leonard Dougal of\nTrumbull station reported that he\nshot at two men whom be saw\nbreaking the window in John\nRomanoff's restaurant, 2800\nEighteenth. The\\ escaped down\nan alley.\nMercury to Hit\n6 Above Tonight\nThe weatherman said today\nthat it'll be colder tonight and to\nmorrow. He expects, the mercury\nto drop to 6 degrees above zero.\nHigh tomorrow will be 20.\nNo immediate letup of the win\ntry blasts was seen for W\u00bb*dnes\niday. Winds w ill In* moderate and\nI from the northwest,\nt Two or three inches of snow\ncovered lower part of the state\nand left some intersections slip\nfiery. Michigan Auto Club urged\ncaution and low speeds on trunk\nlines until sanded.\nAt Harry Siillrin Today!\nJgOg\nJlmx Xt Ui& VB\nf'..\n1 |Sf HnH i\u2019\nB?\n|jr Ml\nDETROIT'S LARGEST EXCLUSIVE CLOTHIER\nTHE TRAGEDY OF TRUMAN:\n(J. S. Loses World Power\nll Acquired During War\nNOTE This is the second of a series hy i\nSamuel Crduther on President Truman's speech of Jan. 3.)\nBy KAMIRL GROWTHER\nOur nation, only a few months ago on the day when\nJapan surrendered, was mightier both absolutely and com\nparatively than any power the world had ever known.\nOur nation is now impotent toi\ndefend itself from aggression and\njwwerless to make way.\nAnd further, by a series of al\nmost incredibly fantastic acts, it\nhas given up not only the ideals\nfor which the people thought they\nwere fighting and sacrificing but\nalso the power to control its ex\nternal relation*, and to an un\nknown degree the power to con\ntrol its internal relations.\nAs a world power, we collapsed\nbefore we got started.\nARMIES DISBANDED\nThe precipitate withdrawal of\nour troops from Europe was in\nresponse to everyone's natural\ndesire to get the bo\\s home, but\nit is not without significance that\nthe Communist periodicals which\nonce were screaming for a second\nfront to help Russia, regardless\nof the cost in American blood,\nscreamed even louder to get the\nboys home when the presence of\na great American army in Europe\ncould have lent weight to our\ndiscussions with Russia on the\nstate of freedom in the little\ncountries that we were supposed\nto have helped liberate.\nWe have already eliminated\nourselves as a military power n\nEurope and are on the way to\ndoing so in Asia.\nHOW IT CAME ABOUT\n\nThe covenant* limiting out\npower to manage ourselves are\ncontained in the international fund\nand the international hank, grow\ning out of the Bret ton Woods\nmeeting; in the United Nations\nOrganization, growing out of the\nSan Francisco conference; and in\nthe as yet obscure food, air anil\nrelief international organizations\nvariously put together at various\nplaces. In the Reciprocal Trade\nAgreements Act, the congress\ndivested itself of its constitutional\nobligation to regulate tariffs.\nDuring the Bret ton Woods\nmeeting, the Hears! newspapers\npointed out that the agreements!\nbeing fashioned had almost\nnothing to do with the stabiliza\ntion of exchanges or any other\nworthy puryiove and a great deal\nto do with draining off American\nresources and rigging the Ameri\ncan dollar. The power to rig the\ndollar is the power to control the\nAmerican economy.\nWARNED OF PITFALLS\nDuring the San Francisco con\nference, the Heacst newspapers\npointed out that the elaborate\ncharter being evolved, although\nfestooned fine words and\nnoble purposes, could be made a\ndevice by which the United States\nmight obligate itself to defend\ntyranny and slavery.\nThe Congress approved the\nBret ton Woods agreements and\nthe San Francisco charter andj\npassed the Reciprocal Trade j\nAgreements Act under tremen\ndous pressure from Hillman's\nPohtiral Action Committee and\nno end of organizations mobilized\nfor the purpose.\nPresident Truman lent himself\nto these campaigns although it\nis now evident that he did not\nknow what any of the obligations\nwere on the ground that he\nneedl'd these votes of confidence\nfor the Big Three meeting at\nPotsdam.\nIt is clear that, if he had in\ntended to do any bargaining, he\nwould have held up the approval\nof these various articles and used\nthem for trading purjmses But\nthe President did no trading at\nPotsdam. He signed what was\ngiven to him.\nSIGNATURE NOT STUDIED\nHe agreed\u2014without any com\nprehension of what he was doing\nto have America enforce the\nMorgenthau plan hv which future\ngenerations of Germans are forr\nj ibly to be kept at a substandard\nlof living\nBy inference, and again without\nknowing what he was doing, he\nendorsed communism by engag\ning to exterminate all other forms\nof collectivism.\nSecretary Byrnes went to Ix>n\ndon and his meeting with Mssrs\nBevin and Molotov broke up in\na row because he and Mr Bevin\nwould not agree for Russia to\nmake puppet states out of Ru\nmania. Bulgaria, and Yugoslavia\nin the way that it had already\nmade puppets out of Czechoslo\nvakia. Poland and the Baltic\nstates.\nMarARTHIR HAMSTRI NG\nMr. Rvrnes. having made a\nstand for the right, made an\nabout-face, went to Moscow and\nin effect told Commissar Motn-~\ntoss that the right was whatever\nthe Soviet wanted it to lie In\naddition, he put the Soviet in a\nposition to interfere with the rule\nof Gen. MacArthur in Japan\nwhich was the one creditable and\nhonorable piece of fine American\nism left in the world\nRussia, having gained or Ix'ing\nabout to gain everything it desired\nin the way of domination of f**o\ni>les. permitted \u2019lie United N iti ns\nfresh arrivals of fine\n\\Y in<l so r-I*n \u00ab*a\nOvereoats\nMffel||iO\nFine wool fleece coats that pad a lot of\nwarmth into a little weight. Single breasted\nwith fly front and slash pockets\u2014in tan, brown,\nblue, oxford.\nOpen Tonight till 9 o'clock\n'Ztewitf Strutt.\nState Street and Shelby\n[Organization with great pomp\nand circumstance to come into\n'bring in London.\nThe single purpose of that or\nganization, outside of providing a\nI haven for lame ducks and a hall\nfor orators, is to make the United\nStates the guarantor of Russian\nimperialism. By the terms of the\ndeed. the*UNO can take no action\nagainst Russia without the unani\nmous consent of the Security\nCouncil. Russia is a member of\nthat council!\nACT OF C HAPULTEI'EC\nAt San Francisco, the American\ndelegation, brilliantly led by Mr,\njStettinius and Senator Vandcn\nl>erg, admitted the Argentine to\nthe conference against the protest\nof Russia and pledged the Ameri\ncan republics that the Art of\nChapultepec would he confirmed\nhy a treaty guaranteeing hemis\nphere solidarity. That meant an\noffensive and defensive alliance of\nail the Americas and a barrier\nagainst Communism.\nThe treaty was due to be drawn\nat Rio I)e Janeiro last November.\nIt was blasted by Undersecretary\nof State Acheson and others in\nthe state department.\nENVOI'S BETRAYED\nc\nThe solemn pledge made to\nthese republics on which a\nhemisphere unity could have been\nbuilt has tx\u00bben broken and\nMessrs Stettmius and Vandenoerg\nseem to have traded their personal\n\u2022honor for the empty privilege of\nbeing delegate* to the UNO.\nOur country under Messrs. Tru\nman and Byrnes, with the mute\nacquiescence of the Senate and\nHouse Foreign Relations Commit\nt\u00ab*es. has followed the Communist\nparty line and has eliminated it\nself as a world power\nAnd. as if to top off the half\ncomic tragf*dy. Great Britain has\narranged for a gift-loan from us\nwhich may or may not be approved\nby the Congress- and Russia is\nstanding by for another and big\nger gift-loan Both hofie to re\nhabilitate themselves at our\nrxpemr -and also to pay their\nquotas in the Bretton Woods\nscheme in order to take more\nof our money.\nNever has a nation nose-dived\nso quickly\nUrges Government\nRetain Press Bureau\nATLANTA. Jan 21 HT'-\nRalph McGill, member of the\nthree-man touring commit tee of\nthe American Society of Newspa\nl\u00bber Editors, has wired President\nTruman urging retention of the\nstate department's information\nprogram, the Atlanta Constitution\nsaid today.","height":"28380","width":"21771"}}
